BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Biomedical Data Science & MSB Program Seminar with Jonathan Garlic
 k\, DDS\, PhD - “The Principles and Practice of 3D Tissue Biology”
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260715T143000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260715T153000
DTSTAMP:20260713T122830Z
UID:geisel-6152-2026-7-15@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://geiselmed.dartmouth.edu/calen
 dar/event_view.php?eid=6152&instance=2026-7-15\n\nDescription:\nThe Depart
 ments of Biomedical Data Science and Molecular and Systems Biology invite 
 you to attend a special seminar in person on Wednesday\, July 15 from 2:30
 -3:30pm at DHMC\, Auditorium H with Jonathan Garlick\, DDS\, PhD\, Profess
 or and Director\, Division of Cancer Biology & Tissue Engineering\, Tufts 
 School of Dental Medicine.\nTalk title: “The Principles and Practice of 
 3D Tissue Biology”\nLight refreshments will be provided on a first-come\
 , first-served basis.\nThe presentation will take place both in person at 
 DHMC\, Auditorium H (and via Zoom) and we encourage as many of you to atte
 nd in person as possible. Please write to biomedical.data.science@dartmout
 h.edu to request the Zoom login details.\nPlease see description below for
  more details.\nPlease invite your fellow faculty colleagues\, research as
 sociates\, graduate trainees\, and postdocs!\nPresentation Summary\nHuman\
 , 3D engineered tissues address fundamental limitations of monolayer cultu
 re\, where cells lose the phenotypic diversity that drives disease biology
  in vivo. This talk outlines universal principles of 3D tissue fabrication
  that can be applied broadly to increase tissue complexity and better reca
 pitulate in vivo biological responses. These principles will be illustrate
 d using human 3D skin equivalents—air-liquid interface cultures grown on
  fibroblast-populated connective tissue matrices—as a model for architec
 turally accurate\, translational disease modeling. By applying these princ
 iples\, we aim to improve in vitro–in vivo correlation for pre-clinical 
 drug screening and therapeutic development.\nBiography\nDr. Jonathan Garli
 ck’s lab research is focused on developing new treatments for chronic di
 seases\, including oral and skin cancer\, scleroderma\, and complications 
 of diabetes.  He has developed 3D tissues as disease models to accelerate 
 the discovery and testing of new drugs. Dr. Garlick established and leads 
 the Civic Science Collective that creates a more inclusive climate for pub
 lic participation in science by fostering equitable and trustworthy relati
 onships between scientists and the communities research hopes to serve. Dr
 . Garlick’s Dialogue Center brings people together in conversation so th
 ey can connect more productively across different worldviews\, identities\
 , power dynamics\, and “cultures” of science. He teaches dialogue-base
 d\, Civic Science courses where students discover how they can gain the sk
 ills they need to create a more inclusive and welcoming climate for partic
 ipation in science.\n\nSponsor / organizer: Biomedical Data Science (  )\n
 \nSource: Geisel\n\nWhy this was included: explicit food-service wording\;
  food keyword near service context\n\nFood availability is inferred from t
 he source listing\; verify details before attending.
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://geiselmed.dartmouth.edu/calendar/event_view.php?eid=6152&insta
 nce=2026-7-15
END:VEVENT
