BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:Publishing Talk: Adam Gianelli & Tomás Q. Morin
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260716T123000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260716T133000
DTSTAMP:20260713T122830Z
UID:dartmouth-82080@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://home.dartmouth.edu/events/eve
 nt?event=82080\n\nDescription:\nIf you've never visited us\,\nthis\nis the
  event to attend! We'll gather around a large table at the Literary Arts 
 Bridge\, Dartmouth's creative writing center\, to share lunch and discuss 
 poetry\, writing\, and publishing with two astonishing poets. The conversa
 tion will be moderated by Dartmouth's own Kate Gibbel\, whose forthcoming
  poetry collection\,\nLittle Sound\,\nis out this fall.\nAbout the Poets:\
 nAdam Giannelli is the author of\nTremulous Hinge\n(University of Iowa Pre
 ssOpens in a new window\, 2017)\, winner of the Iowa Poetry Prize. He is a
 lso the translator of a selection of prose poems by Marosa di Giorgio\,\nD
 iadem\n(BOA EditionsOpens in a new window\, 2012)\, which was shortlisted 
 for the PEN Award for Poetry in Translation\, and the editor of\nHigh Lone
 some\n(Oberlin College PressOpens in a new window\, 2006)\, a collection o
 f critical essays on Charles Wright. His writing has appeared in\nPoetry\,
  Kenyon Review\, New England Review\, Ploughshares\, Atlantic\, New York T
 imes Magazine\, New Criterion\,\nand elsewhere. His work has been supporte
 d by fellowships and residencies from several institutions\, including the
  National Endowment for the Arts\, Fulbright Program\, James Merrill House
 \, Bread Loaf Writers’ Conference\, Sewanee Writers’ Conference\, Yadd
 o\, and MacDowell. He has taught at Oberlin College\, Hamilton College\, C
 olby College\, and Purdue University.\nTomás Q. Morin\nis the author of t
 he novel Cat Love and the forthcoming poetry collection\nMy Favorite Thing
 s\n. He is also wrote the memoirs\nLet Me Count the Ways\nand\nWhere Are Y
 ou From: Letters to My Son\n\, as well as the poetry collections\nMachete\
 , Patient Zero\n\, and\nA Larger Country\n. He is coeditor\, with Mari L
 ’Esperance\, of the anthology\nComing Close: Forty Essays on Philip Levi
 ne\n\, and a translator of\nThe Heights of Macchu Picchu\nby Pablo Neruda.
  He is a fellow of the Guggenheim Foundation and the National Endowment fo
 r the Arts. He teaches at Rice University.\nAbout the Moderator:\nAbout th
 e Katherine Gibbel’s poems have been published in\nThe Iowa Review\n\,\
 njubilat\n\,\nSecond Factory\n(ugly duckling presse)\, and elsewhere. Her 
 chapbook\nPrairie\nwas published by Ethel Press in 2020. She edits and pri
 nts\nSend Me Press\,\na monthly series of letterpress printed postcard bro
 adsides. She holds an MFA in poetry from the Iowa Writers’ Workshop and 
 lives in Hartland\, Vermont. Her first collection\,\nLittle Sound\n\, will
  be published by the University of Chicago Press Phoenix Poets Series in F
 all 2026.\n\nSponsor / organizer: Literary Arts Bridge\n\nAudience: Public
 \n\nSource: Dartmouth\n\nWhy this was included: Free Food category\; expli
 cit food-service wording\; food or meal keyword in title/summary\n\nFood a
 vailability is inferred from the source listing\; verify details before at
 tending.
LOCATION:Literary Arts Bridge (7 Lebanon St. Suite 105)
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://home.dartmouth.edu/events/event?event=82080
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
SUMMARY:26Xpressions: Common Roots
DTSTART;TZID=America/New_York:20260716T180000
DTEND;TZID=America/New_York:20260716T190000
DTSTAMP:20260713T122830Z
UID:dartmouth-82024@free-food-dartmouth
DESCRIPTION:Original event page(s):\nhttps://home.dartmouth.edu/events/eve
 nt?event=82024\n\nDescription:\nLooking to green up your living space but 
 don't quite have a green thumb yet? Join us for Common Roots\, an exciting
  collaborative event presented by OPAL and the Outdoor Programs Office (OP
 O) as part of Xpressions of Dartmouth 2026. Intentionally designed for beg
 inners\, this hands-on workshop breaks down the barriers to gardening and 
 gives anyone interested in house plants a welcoming place to start. You wi
 ll have the opportunity to take home your very own plant trimmings\, and t
 he experts from OPO will be on-site to teach you exactly how to care for t
 hese beautiful indigenous plants. To sweeten the evening\, we will be serv
 ing up a nostalgic favorite: Mud Cups\, the classic childhood treat made o
 f chocolate pudding\, crushed Oreo "dirt\," and gummy worms.\nThe learning
  doesn't have to stop when the hour is up\, either. To help you connect ev
 en deeper with the local environment\, OPO will be hosting a follow-up nat
 ure walk the very next day to explore these indigenous plants in their nat
 ural habitats.\nWhether you are a seasoned plant parent or someone who has
  historically struggled to keep a succulent alive\, Common Roots is the pe
 rfect opportunity to dig into a new skill\, enjoy a sweet treat\, and find
  your community. All materials\, plants\, and snacks are completely free\,
  and absolutely no prior gardening experience is required — just bring y
 our curiosity and an appetite for fun!\n\nSponsor / organizer: Office of P
 luralism and Leadership (OPAL)\n\nAudience: Alumni\, Faculty\, Postdoc\, P
 ublic\, Staff\, Students-Graduate\, Students-Undergraduate\n\nSource: Dart
 mouth\n\nWhy this was included: Free Food category\; food keyword near ser
 vice context\n\nFood availability is inferred from the source listing\; ve
 rify details before attending.
LOCATION:Baker Lawn
STATUS:CONFIRMED
URL:https://home.dartmouth.edu/events/event?event=82024
END:VEVENT
